        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The observations will be carried out using a 1875MHz bandwidth in both bands. This ensures the largest possible bandwidth with a width of 1630km/s for CO(3-2) and 814km/s for CO(6-5) in order to cover the entire spectra of the lines which are 350km/s wide as well as the continuum. We smooth the spectral resolution to 1938MHz (1.6km/s and 0.8km/s in the two bands respectively) in order to reduce the data rate and we intend to further smooth the line emission during the data analysis to about 20km/s in order to increase the signal to noise.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We intend to map the warm molecular torus of the Circinus galaxy as a natural extension of the established hot inner torus, which has a size of about a parsec (~0.05 arcsec). With the observations proposed here, we aim specifically at mapping the small scale structure of the torus such as filaments and clumps and resolving their kinematics, all well inside the circumnuclear starforming regions starting at a few tens of parsec (~2.0arcsec). As a consequence, the largest available baseline configuration providing the highest possible spatial resolution is required. A single pointing with the 12m array in the most extended (C36-7) configuration will probe spatial scales of 0.04 to 0.5arcsec for CO(3-2) in Band 7. A very similar resolution will be reached for CO(6-5) allowing us to construct excitation temperature maps and to directly compare the two transitions.

We clearly emphasize that we are not interested in the extended emission coming from the circumnuclear starburst or the large scale outflow. These will be studied by a complementary proposal (PI: Francesco Costagliola, "Spatially resolved chemistry around an obscured AGN"). The two studies combined will build a coherent picture of the kinematics of the molecular gas in the Circinus Galaxy, from the sub-parsec to the kiloparsec scale.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our main goal is to obtain a map of the molecular material in CO(3-2) and CO(6-5). With APEX, a peak flux density of ~40Jy was measured for both lines (see Fig. 2 in the scientific justification). From the large velocity gradient modelling, an effective emission size of 2 arcsec in diameter was derived. This means we arithmetically obtain an average flux of ~20 mJy per resolution element of ALMA for both CO(3-2) and CO(6-5) and the proposed high angular resolution. We nevertheless expect the emission to be more concentrated towards the nucleus.

Due to the long baselines, we assume 70% missing flux for CO(3-2), because about that fraction comes from the more extended low excitation component. Hence we expect a final flux of ~6 mJy per resolution element. For a detection with a signal to noise ratio of about 10 and a velocity resolution of 20km/s, the exposure time calculator yields an integration time of about 40min for CO(3-2) with 0.6 mJy/beam sensitivity for PWV=0.7mm. Including overheads and calibration, this adds up to a total of 2.0 hours of ALMA observing time in band 7.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
